00:02:42.604 --> 00:02:44.270
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Well, to that point

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:45.950
of dealing with
Jason again, this

00:02:45.950 --> 00:02:49.010
is your third film
in what some have

00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:51.530
said is even sort
of a trilogy, Jason,

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:55.280
with "Juno" and "Young Adult,"
which you did with Charlize.

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:57.320
JASON REITMAN: It's like
"Lord of the Rings."

00:02:57.320 --> 00:02:58.150
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Just like that.

00:02:58.150 --> 00:02:58.590
JASON REITMAN: Yeah.

00:02:58.590 --> 00:03:00.290
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Yeah, so what's

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:02.600
important to you about
these three films

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.160
and the sequence
of them together?

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:07.760
JASON REITMAN: I mean, when
I met Diablo over a decade

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:10.370
ago now, I don't think I
could have ever guessed

00:03:10.370 --> 00:03:13.700
that we were starting this
trajectory with each other,

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:16.700
that somehow we were going to
be in a kind of storytelling

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:17.450
marriage.

00:03:17.450 --> 00:03:21.599
And now, of course, I
just hope it continues

00:03:21.599 --> 00:03:23.390
for the rest of our
lives, and that we keep

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:25.335
on making movies like this.

00:03:25.335 --> 00:03:25.835
I think--

00:03:25.835 --> 00:03:27.590
RON LIVINGSTONE: Do you
remember your anniversary?

00:03:27.590 --> 00:03:28.923
Because that's a big part of it.

00:03:28.923 --> 00:03:31.100
JASON REITMAN: Oh, fuck.

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:31.880
I blew it already.

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:33.254
I remember the
first time we met.

00:03:33.254 --> 00:03:35.930
We met at this place called
the Father's Daughter

00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:38.930
over on Fairfax near the Grove,
and they have a bar in there.

00:03:38.930 --> 00:03:40.760
And she ordered a dirty Martini.

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:42.290
I ordered a Diet
Coke, and it was

00:03:42.290 --> 00:03:48.100
just very on par for our
relationship going forward.

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:52.080
But "Juno" was a movie
about growing up too fast,

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:55.430
and "Young Adult" was a
movie about growing up

00:03:55.430 --> 00:03:56.360
a little too slow.

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.970
And this is a movie about
that moment when you realize

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:01.160
that you have to grow up.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:03.140
And you have to turn
a chapter on your life

00:04:03.140 --> 00:04:06.920
and create room so that your
child can occupy the space

00:04:06.920 --> 00:04:08.917
that you were occupying.

00:04:08.917 --> 00:04:11.000
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: And
tell us a little bit more

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:16.339
about what attracts you to
this and to Diablo's writing.

00:04:16.339 --> 00:04:19.694
JASON REITMAN: You know,
it's funny, Charlize, Diablo,

00:04:19.694 --> 00:04:21.110
and I are all
around the same age.

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:24.327
And although we came
from different places,

00:04:24.327 --> 00:04:25.910
there's some sort
of connective tissue

00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:29.280
that, when Diablo
writes a script,

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:32.950
she's articulating things
that we've all been feeling.

00:04:32.950 --> 00:04:35.840
And there's something that
Diablo does really well,

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:38.440
where she writes about an idea
that we can all relate to,

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:40.420
which is not knowing
where you're supposed

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:43.330
to be in the arc of your life.

00:04:43.330 --> 00:04:46.990
I think we all often have this
feeling like, am I behind?

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:47.590
Am I ahead?

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:49.006
Am I doing this
at the right time?

00:04:49.006 --> 00:04:52.030
What was I supposed to
do by now at this age?

00:04:52.030 --> 00:04:56.516
Whether it's work, with family,
have you bought a house yet?

00:04:56.516 --> 00:04:57.640
Have you done this or that?

00:04:57.640 --> 00:05:00.190
And so much of her
writing is about that,

00:05:00.190 --> 00:05:03.120
and for whatever reason, I
think it connects all of us.

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:05.440
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Yeah, so to that point,

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:08.590
I'd love to speak to the
dynamic between the two

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:11.740
characters of Marlo and of
Tully, Mackenzie, which you

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:16.000
play, and the dynamics that you
explore in those relationships

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.360
between women.

00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:22.870
There's episodes of judgment or
younger self versus older self

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:23.750
kind of feelings.

00:05:23.750 --> 00:05:28.740
So tell me about the dynamic
between these two women.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:31.770
MACKENZIE DAVIS: I mean,
it was an interesting role

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:38.100
to play because of the space
that it occupied in somebody

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.470
else's life and
trying to find out

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:46.830
how you can be your own shoulder
to cry on and support system

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:50.100
without becoming like a
really malevolent force

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:52.579
in that person's life.

00:05:52.579 --> 00:05:53.120
I don't know.

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:54.146
I thought it was--

00:05:54.146 --> 00:05:56.520
I mean, I think we'll just
reiterate the same things over

00:05:56.520 --> 00:06:01.860
and over, but just a really
honest approach to how lovely

00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:04.230
and shitty it can
be to be female.

00:06:04.230 --> 00:06:06.270
And I haven't had
kids, but I have

00:06:06.270 --> 00:06:07.530
been a woman my whole life.

00:06:07.530 --> 00:06:11.760
And there were so
many things that it

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:14.460
felt like Diablo was telling
secrets from my own life,

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:17.970
and you were like
how do you know that?

00:06:17.970 --> 00:06:22.920
And yeah, I just thought it was
a lovely female friendship that

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:27.750
was really honest
and not sugary sweet.

00:06:27.750 --> 00:06:32.621
But-- do you want
to say anything?

00:06:32.621 --> 00:06:34.620
CHARLIZE THERON: I mean,
having been the younger

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:35.661
one in the relationship--

00:06:35.661 --> 00:06:38.180
[LAUGHING]

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:42.200
No, you said it so beautifully.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:43.600
I totally agree with you.

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:48.150
I mean, I think Diablo doesn't
know how to not write honestly,

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:52.320
and I think she loves
that space where we all

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:54.030
live, whether you're
a woman or a man,

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:56.100
that's maybe not so pretty.

00:06:56.100 --> 00:06:58.920
And I know for myself,
I'm very much--

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:02.840
I'm fascinated by that space.

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:06.520
And so to have a writer
and a filmmaker who

00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:09.340
really wants to go and explore
that space, it's really--

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:14.020
it's heaven to get a job like
that where all of us get--

00:07:14.020 --> 00:07:17.800
we get to live in the
skin of real people who

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:20.250
are going through maybe not
so nice things and maybe

00:07:20.250 --> 00:07:23.980
are not behaving in
the best possible ways

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:25.940
that they could
in those moments.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:31.130
But it's human, and it's
exploring that human condition,

00:07:31.130 --> 00:07:32.977
and I love that.

00:07:32.977 --> 00:07:34.060
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: One--

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:36.190
another moment, I
remember from the film

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:39.400
is there's an episode
in a coffee shop

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:43.030
where you are clearly
very, very pregnant,

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:44.541
and you're ordering a decaf.

00:07:44.541 --> 00:07:45.040
And yet--

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:46.300
CHARLIZE THERON: How dare I?

00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:46.800
How dare I?

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:48.258
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
And yet you're

00:07:48.258 --> 00:07:50.860
facing all this judgment from
this woman who's giving you

00:07:50.860 --> 00:07:54.580
dirty looks, and can you talk
about that judgmental part

00:07:54.580 --> 00:07:58.090
that you explore there, that
women do face pretty constantly

00:07:58.090 --> 00:07:58.660
in society?

00:07:58.660 --> 00:07:59.743
CHARLIZE THERON: Oh, yeah.

00:07:59.743 --> 00:08:04.840
Yeah, I mean, I think that
we definitely live in a world

00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:08.200
where we're just so hard,
especially on parents,

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:10.750
because all of a
sudden, they're carrying

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:12.107
this other little human.

00:08:12.107 --> 00:08:13.690
And I feel like the
world almost feels

00:08:13.690 --> 00:08:16.120
like they can step in and have
a judgment because it's not

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:16.750
really you.

00:08:16.750 --> 00:08:18.910
It's that little person
that they don't even

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:20.860
know that's living
inside of you.

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:22.300
And I definitely
have been with--

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:24.130
I didn't have
pregnancies myself,

00:08:24.130 --> 00:08:27.340
but just with my adopted kids.

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:29.230
I remember a mom
pulling me aside,

00:08:29.230 --> 00:08:34.090
and she was like you should
not be using formula,

00:08:34.090 --> 00:08:38.799
and I can hook you up with
some real breast milk.

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:43.690
And it was just like,
[SIGH],, and my kids

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:45.270
are fine as of right now.

00:08:45.270 --> 00:08:47.440
They're still good.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:49.540
They're doing OK on the formula.

00:08:52.647 --> 00:08:54.230
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
So I'd love to go

00:08:54.230 --> 00:08:56.800
a little bit deeper on that
because the last movie that I

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:59.410
saw you in was "Atomic
Blonde," very different

00:08:59.410 --> 00:09:00.860
type of a female character.

00:09:00.860 --> 00:09:02.276
CHARLIZE THERON:
Little bit, yeah.

00:09:02.276 --> 00:09:05.170
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: Yeah, it
was a real super, kick-ass spy

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:05.970
movie.

00:09:05.970 --> 00:09:09.670
And you have a production
company, Denver and Delilah,

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:11.770
that was written up
in "Variety" not long

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:14.710
ago for really backing those
powerful female-centric

00:09:14.710 --> 00:09:15.610
stories.

00:09:15.610 --> 00:09:19.300
So can you talk a little bit
about how you pick your roles

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:23.170
and how your company
decides on its projects?

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:28.420
CHARLIZE THERON: Yeah, we have
a cool little thing going on

00:09:28.420 --> 00:09:29.950
with Denver and Delilah.

00:09:29.950 --> 00:09:32.650
We're definitely fortunate
enough to be in a place

00:09:32.650 --> 00:09:37.590
where we do have
a little bit more

00:09:37.590 --> 00:09:40.470
of a luxury, where we
can greenlight things

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:44.070
that might not get greenlit.

00:09:44.070 --> 00:09:48.210
A film like "Atomic
Blonde" very easily

00:09:48.210 --> 00:09:51.840
could have been a
male-driven film.

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:54.845
And to be able to have
a little bit of that,

00:09:54.845 --> 00:09:56.720
to be in that position
where you can actually

00:09:56.720 --> 00:10:00.890
take a film like that and
get a studio like Universal

00:10:00.890 --> 00:10:03.740
to back it, that's a
really nice place to be in,

00:10:03.740 --> 00:10:06.980
and I don't ever take
that for granted.

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:08.740
We're also trying to--

00:10:08.740 --> 00:10:11.960
we do a lot of
television and film,

00:10:11.960 --> 00:10:17.120
and so we're really trying to
not just, with female stories,

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:22.490
but really paying
attention to bringing women

00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:25.899
into the positions that they're
just very strong in right now.

00:10:25.899 --> 00:10:27.440
And so we have a
lot of projects that

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.140
are maybe not
directed by females,

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:32.710
but they're all
female producers.

00:10:32.710 --> 00:10:37.130
And so I think being in
that position where you

00:10:37.130 --> 00:10:39.770
can put your foot down, and--

00:10:39.770 --> 00:10:42.110
I was just on a film that we
produced, and I walked on,

00:10:42.110 --> 00:10:44.900
and our sound department
didn't have one woman on it.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:47.120
And we had a bunch of
female actresses on it,

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:50.150
and I was like, guys, what-- no.

00:10:50.150 --> 00:10:52.845
We need a lady here to be
dealing with the bra straps.

00:10:55.680 --> 00:10:58.310
It's just a nice place to be
in, and for me as an actor,

00:10:58.310 --> 00:11:00.980
it's not necessarily always
so that I can star in it.

00:11:00.980 --> 00:11:05.210
It's nice that I can
take ownership and guide

00:11:05.210 --> 00:11:08.450
a little bit of the stuff
that I do want to explore,

00:11:08.450 --> 00:11:11.180
that you do get tired of
kind of waiting around

00:11:11.180 --> 00:11:14.577
for a filmmaker or a writer
to come around and hand you

00:11:14.577 --> 00:11:15.410
something like that.

00:11:15.410 --> 00:11:17.780
So you can kind of step
in and develop things

00:11:17.780 --> 00:11:20.570
that you're interested
in, and I love that.

00:11:20.570 --> 00:11:24.620
And I like that it can-- that
I can be as diverse as I want

00:11:24.620 --> 00:11:28.060
to be, and that, I think, is
one of the hardest things--

00:11:28.060 --> 00:11:30.890
or was for me in my career.

00:11:30.890 --> 00:11:34.220
You have garnered some
success in some genre,

00:11:34.220 --> 00:11:36.860
and then that's all
everybody wants you to do.

00:11:36.860 --> 00:11:39.950
And having a production company
gets me to do different things

00:11:39.950 --> 00:11:44.580
and not regurgitate the same
thing over and over and over.

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:46.380
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Yeah, that's--

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:49.680
that seeking of diversity
in creativity and thought

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:53.390
and female centric is something
we really value at Google,

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:54.690
and I do on my team as well.

00:11:54.690 --> 00:11:55.930
So thank you.

00:11:55.930 --> 00:11:57.259
CHARLIZE THERON: Oh, cool.

00:11:57.259 --> 00:11:58.300
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: Ron?

00:11:58.300 --> 00:11:58.760
RON LIVINGSTONE: Yes?

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:00.343
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
You're from Iowa.

