00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:35.640
RON LIVINGSTONE:
Yeah, obviously,

00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:38.620
because I'm raising two girls
to enter into the world,

00:12:38.620 --> 00:12:44.150
I'd like the world to be
a welcoming and nice place

00:12:44.150 --> 00:12:45.540
for them to be.

00:12:45.540 --> 00:12:47.060
And I want them to
be valued, and I

00:12:47.060 --> 00:12:52.180
want them to be empowered, and
I want them to feel strong.

00:12:52.180 --> 00:12:57.680
They're pretty strong right now,
so I feel really good about it.

00:12:57.680 --> 00:13:00.860
Yeah, and then the rest of
the stuff, I guess we'll--

00:13:00.860 --> 00:13:03.650
I guess we'll get to.

00:13:03.650 --> 00:13:05.400
What I like about this--

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:07.960
the way that this set up
is-- and you talked about

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:09.410
the authenticity--

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:18.080
is I feel like there's a
husband mold of what husbands

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:22.550
do in the child-rearing area.

00:13:22.550 --> 00:13:25.460
And in real life, the
bar is a lot lower

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:26.810
than what you see in the movies.

00:13:26.810 --> 00:13:29.210
In the movies, it's
like we give them

00:13:29.210 --> 00:13:31.670
a lot of the benefit of
the doubt and credit.

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:35.480
And so this
character is really--

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:39.050
he's contributing closer
to what husbands generally

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:42.563
actually contribute and think
they're doing a great job.

00:13:45.461 --> 00:13:51.650
So I don't know how that relates
to the female empowerment

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:59.380
element overall, but
it's a wife part.

00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:02.000
I'm playing a wife part,
is what they would call it.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.470
And it's kind of great
that it's flipped around

00:14:05.470 --> 00:14:08.370
because I know my wife has
played a lot of wife parts

00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:11.810
and made some wonderful
things out of them.

00:14:11.810 --> 00:14:14.480
So that was a really
good challenge,

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:18.860
of I've got to take this
guy who's in a supportive

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:24.445
functioning role and figure out,
well, how can we make it real.

00:14:24.445 --> 00:14:26.820
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: Anything
you would add there, Jason?

00:14:26.820 --> 00:14:28.403
JASON REITMAN: I
mean, the funny thing

00:14:28.403 --> 00:14:31.350
is that I'd really like to
make a movie for my daughter.

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:34.440
But I've made eight
movies so far,

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:37.390
and she hasn't seen any of
them because they're all rated

00:14:37.390 --> 00:14:39.760
R or about teen pregnancy.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:46.050
So I have a lot of
conversations waiting for me.

00:14:46.050 --> 00:14:47.670
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: Got it.

00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:51.080
Well, another thing I'd like
to touch on with you all is

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:51.580
you've--

00:14:51.580 --> 00:14:53.746
and you've mentioned a
little bit of this, Charlize.

00:14:53.746 --> 00:14:56.670
You've both done small
screen and big screen work,

00:14:56.670 --> 00:14:59.190
and in my role here
at Google, I work

00:14:59.190 --> 00:15:01.680
quite a bit with
the film studios

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:02.860
and also the broadcasters.

00:15:02.860 --> 00:15:04.890
So I think it's
interesting what's

00:15:04.890 --> 00:15:08.040
going on between small
and big screen these days,

00:15:08.040 --> 00:15:10.260
and also, I think
it's really important

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:13.570
that these kind of stories make
it to the big screen still,

00:15:13.570 --> 00:15:16.800
and it's not just a world
of sequels and blockbusters.

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:19.094
So I thought maybe
you all could talk--

00:15:19.094 --> 00:15:20.760
JASON REITMAN: Though
this is a trilogy.

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:21.830
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Yes, that's true--

00:15:21.830 --> 00:15:22.650
well, that's true.

00:15:22.650 --> 00:15:25.860
That's true, but with
unique characters, yeah.

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:28.952
So I'd love to just talk
about how do we encourage

00:15:28.952 --> 00:15:30.660
and make sure that
these types of stories

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:34.229
are told on the
big screen as well.

00:15:34.229 --> 00:15:35.770
RON LIVINGSTONE: I
mean, the best way

00:15:35.770 --> 00:15:39.120
to do it is to make them.

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:43.990
I mean, that's, I
think, the first step.

00:15:43.990 --> 00:15:47.320
And that's-- thank
God you're doing that.

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:50.510
I don't really feel that there's
that much of a difference.

00:15:50.510 --> 00:15:53.301
The camera's the same
size in any case,

00:15:53.301 --> 00:15:55.300
but whether it's a big
screen or a small screen,

00:15:55.300 --> 00:15:56.480
that stuff all comes later.

00:15:56.480 --> 00:15:58.570
I feel like when--

00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:00.530
you're probably maybe
thinking about that,

00:16:00.530 --> 00:16:05.620
but when I show
up to work, it's--

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:08.350
I'm not thinking
about the screen.

00:16:08.350 --> 00:16:10.480
And I think people have
a great relationship--

00:16:10.480 --> 00:16:12.220
I feel like the
difference-- and people

00:16:12.220 --> 00:16:14.570
have some pretty big screens
in their houses now, too.

00:16:14.570 --> 00:16:15.460
JENNIFER VAN
FOSSEN: That's true.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:16.540
RON LIVINGSTONE: And there's
going to be a lot of people who

00:16:16.540 --> 00:16:18.805
watch this on-- they'll
download it or--

00:16:18.805 --> 00:16:19.930
JASON REITMAN: Their phone.

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:22.305
RON LIVINGSTONE: Yeah, or
they'll pirate it or something.

00:16:22.305 --> 00:16:23.850
Yeah, exactly.

00:16:23.850 --> 00:16:27.340
So yeah-- to me,
I think it's more

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:30.040
of a thing of when
the big screen still

00:16:30.040 --> 00:16:32.369
has that place for
this is an event.

00:16:32.369 --> 00:16:33.910
We're going to give
this our evening.

00:16:33.910 --> 00:16:35.410
We're going to get
out of our house.

00:16:35.410 --> 00:16:38.900
We're going to go sit down,
buy expensive popcorn,

00:16:38.900 --> 00:16:40.150
and we're locked into this.

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:42.110
We can't flip the channel
if we don't like it.

00:16:42.110 --> 00:16:45.790
We can walk out, but that's
a very dramatic thing.

00:16:45.790 --> 00:16:49.660
So it's-- yeah, it's nice
that we're giving adult fare,

00:16:49.660 --> 00:16:52.886
I think, I guess,
if you're an adult.

00:16:52.886 --> 00:16:55.510
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: So it's not
so much about the screen then.

00:16:55.510 --> 00:16:57.070
It's about the
projects getting made

00:16:57.070 --> 00:17:00.559
and the stories being
told regardless.

00:17:00.559 --> 00:17:03.100
JASON REITMAN: I hope we hold
onto the collective experience.

00:17:03.100 --> 00:17:03.970
That's the important thing.

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:05.553
I think there's a
lot of conversations

00:17:05.553 --> 00:17:08.861
about screens and sound, and
that's all well and good.

00:17:08.861 --> 00:17:11.319
It's nice, although I find I
go to the movies all the time,

00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:15.050
and I think, man, why
won't they turn this up?

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:17.050
I wish they would play
movies louder in theaters

00:17:17.050 --> 00:17:19.480
and change the bulbs in
the projectors more often,

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:21.920
but I'm also a nerd.

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:26.560
But what I think is important
is the collective experience,

00:17:26.560 --> 00:17:31.376
is you go to the movies, you're
with a bunch of strangers,

00:17:31.376 --> 00:17:34.000
and you're all laughing together
or you're all crying together.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:35.333
You're all being moved together.

00:17:35.333 --> 00:17:37.270
You're all realizing
something together,

00:17:37.270 --> 00:17:39.060
and that is a very
rare experience.

00:17:39.060 --> 00:17:41.050
I think it's an
important experience.

00:17:41.050 --> 00:17:42.770
I mean, it certainly has
been throughout my childhood.

00:17:42.770 --> 00:17:43.170
I love movies.

00:17:43.170 --> 00:17:45.628
I try going to the movies as
many times a week as possible.

00:17:47.870 --> 00:17:51.190
And by the way, I love
television, and I watch a lot,

00:17:51.190 --> 00:17:52.570
and I binge a lot as well.

00:17:52.570 --> 00:17:55.512
I think it's a great
form of entertainment.

00:17:55.512 --> 00:17:57.970
What I'd hate to lose, though,
is the collective experience

00:17:57.970 --> 00:18:01.990
that doesn't only happen for
movies like "Black Panther,"

00:18:01.990 --> 00:18:07.360
but also happens for tiny movies
that can really change minds

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:09.760
and move us because there's
something different about

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:12.280
watching a movie at home alone
and having that experience--

00:18:12.280 --> 00:18:14.590
which is moving,
but it's alone--

00:18:14.590 --> 00:18:17.596
and having it as a community
with people you don't know.

00:18:17.596 --> 00:18:18.970
You all showed up
at this theater

00:18:18.970 --> 00:18:20.674
from maybe all
parts of the city.

00:18:20.674 --> 00:18:22.090
You all come from
different lives,

00:18:22.090 --> 00:18:24.400
and now, you're all
laughing together.

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:28.870
And I think the thing that I
fear losing the most is that.

00:18:28.870 --> 00:18:30.620
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
That's a great point.

00:18:30.620 --> 00:18:32.661
So if the audience
wants to get ready,

00:18:32.661 --> 00:18:34.535
I think we're going to
do a little bit of Q&amp;A

00:18:34.535 --> 00:18:37.040
if you guys want to
get ready for that.

00:18:37.040 --> 00:18:39.980
And I'm curious,
Jason, is there a movie

00:18:39.980 --> 00:18:42.030
that was like that for you?

00:18:42.030 --> 00:18:44.252
Can you think back?

00:18:44.252 --> 00:18:46.335
JASON REITMAN: I mean, a
movie theater experience?

00:18:46.335 --> 00:18:47.120
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Yeah, that collective--

00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:48.828
JASON REITMAN: I mean,
there's a hundred,

00:18:48.828 --> 00:18:52.610
but I remember lining up
to see "Pulp Fiction,"

00:18:52.610 --> 00:18:54.740
and I was in high school.

00:18:54.740 --> 00:18:58.134
And that was one of the
great nights of my life.

00:18:58.134 --> 00:18:59.800
I mean, I think about
that night the way

00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:04.430
that people think about
lining up for some show

00:19:04.430 --> 00:19:07.260
at CBGB's in the
'70s or something.

00:19:07.260 --> 00:19:08.700
That was a life changer.

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:09.310
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: Yeah.

00:19:09.310 --> 00:19:10.100
How about the rest of you?

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:12.100
Can you think of a title
that was really moving?

00:19:12.100 --> 00:19:13.430
CHARLIZE THERON: I just--

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:19.201
I was sharing this with Jason,
and I think my friend is here

00:19:19.201 --> 00:19:20.450
who's a producer on this, too.

00:19:20.450 --> 00:19:23.750
Beth Kono and I went to
go see "Shape of Water,"

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:29.812
and we're both kind of
dead inside as people.

00:19:29.812 --> 00:19:31.940
We don't have a lot of emotion.

00:19:31.940 --> 00:19:36.532
And I started crying
so uncontrollably.

00:19:36.532 --> 00:19:38.990
I was literally, like, oh, my
god, this is so embarrassing,

00:19:38.990 --> 00:19:41.060
and then I just looked
over, and she was crying,

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:43.625
and I was like, thank you.

00:19:43.625 --> 00:19:44.510
Thank you.

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:46.680
I'm not a weirdo.

00:19:46.680 --> 00:19:48.110
But it's like Jason said.

00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:51.800
I could have never
experienced that at home,

00:19:51.800 --> 00:19:57.820
and it's nice to have that
conversation after, too.

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:01.490
The credits start rolling,
and you start talking about it

00:20:01.490 --> 00:20:04.130
collectively, and there's
something nice about that.

00:20:04.130 --> 00:20:07.490
And I do think sometimes people
have experiences-- they watch

00:20:07.490 --> 00:20:11.044
films at home, and they don't
have the same experience

00:20:11.044 --> 00:20:13.460
that you do when you're in
that theater with other people.

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:14.286
Something happens.

00:20:14.286 --> 00:20:15.660
Maybe it's the
expensive popcorn.

00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:18.440
I don't know, but something
definitely happens.

00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:19.910
For me, it did.

00:20:19.910 --> 00:20:22.460
I'm not dead, turns out.

00:20:22.460 --> 00:20:23.320
JASON REITMAN: OK.

