00:23:50.350 --> 00:23:54.470
The only name that was ever
brought up was Mackenzie,

00:23:54.470 --> 00:23:59.480
and I mean, for me, when I
read the script, because it

00:23:59.480 --> 00:24:04.340
was so intricate, this
relationship between us,

00:24:04.340 --> 00:24:08.390
I definitely read
it in that sense.

00:24:08.390 --> 00:24:10.580
And so I was like, that's
going to be interesting.

00:24:10.580 --> 00:24:11.621
What do you do with this?

00:24:11.621 --> 00:24:13.760
And Mackenzie showed
up, and it was just

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:17.690
so beautifully weird and odd.

00:24:17.690 --> 00:24:21.050
And pretty much from the
moment that I met her,

00:24:21.050 --> 00:24:25.760
I was just like this, and so
it was perfect for the film.

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:27.080
And then she ends up--

00:24:27.080 --> 00:24:30.050
she's a cool girl, so it was
nice to be on set with her

00:24:30.050 --> 00:24:32.780
and to share this
experience with her.

00:24:32.780 --> 00:24:34.040
MACKENZIE DAVIS: Thank you.

00:24:34.040 --> 00:24:35.373
CHARLIZE THERON: You're welcome.

00:24:37.110 --> 00:24:41.030
MACKENZIE DAVIS: Yeah, I feel
like we didn't plan anything

00:24:41.030 --> 00:24:41.820
out too much.

00:24:41.820 --> 00:24:45.235
We just talked a bit about--

00:24:45.235 --> 00:24:46.610
I remember that
breakfast that we

00:24:46.610 --> 00:24:49.040
had in that weird hotel
in the Sutton Hotel,

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:52.270
where we just talked
about getting older

00:24:52.270 --> 00:24:55.790
in a really normal way.

00:24:55.790 --> 00:24:57.470
I don't know.

00:24:57.470 --> 00:24:59.210
We have the same
body type, and what

00:24:59.210 --> 00:25:01.544
it's like to be used to
the way your body behaves

00:25:01.544 --> 00:25:02.960
for your whole
life, and then what

00:25:02.960 --> 00:25:05.459
happens when it starts behaving
in a different way, and just

00:25:05.459 --> 00:25:10.580
simple things that can bond
you to someone quite easily

00:25:10.580 --> 00:25:11.239
and make you--

00:25:11.239 --> 00:25:11.780
I don't know.

00:25:11.780 --> 00:25:14.840
There's certain-- this
sounds like something that

00:25:14.840 --> 00:25:17.720
"Cosmopolitan Magazine" would
say, but there are something--

00:25:17.720 --> 00:25:20.240
certain secrets of being
female that can make you

00:25:20.240 --> 00:25:23.030
feel very close to
someone immediately

00:25:23.030 --> 00:25:27.947
without needing to map out
a whole plan right away.

00:25:27.947 --> 00:25:30.530
CHARLIZE THERON: I think she's
also one of the funniest people

00:25:30.530 --> 00:25:34.790
I've ever been around, and
so that's just so disarming.

00:25:34.790 --> 00:25:37.490
And I think, instantly, we
really connected on that.

00:25:37.490 --> 00:25:39.920
I was just-- every time
I was around, I was--

00:25:39.920 --> 00:25:45.080
because I was not the
funnest person on the shoot.

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:47.630
I dealt with depression for
the first time in my life,

00:25:47.630 --> 00:25:51.260
and my body was just not
happy, and my mind was unhappy,

00:25:51.260 --> 00:25:52.670
and my soul was unhappy.

00:25:52.670 --> 00:25:57.680
And being around her was just
real joy, and I think we--

00:25:57.680 --> 00:25:59.930
I definitely got-- whether
she liked it or not,

00:25:59.930 --> 00:26:02.390
I got close to her through that.

00:26:02.390 --> 00:26:03.660
I was very happy when she--

00:26:03.660 --> 00:26:05.718
Ron, I was happy when
you were there, too.

00:26:05.718 --> 00:26:07.060
RON LIVINGSTONE: OK, it was OK.

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:09.310
CHARLIZE THERON: I was happy
when you were there, too.

00:26:09.310 --> 00:26:10.190
RON LIVINGSTONE: Sure.

00:26:10.190 --> 00:26:11.689
CHARLIZE THERON:
In a different way.

00:26:11.689 --> 00:26:13.040
RON LIVINGSTONE: Yeah.

00:26:13.040 --> 00:26:13.565
CHARLIZE THERON: I love Ron.

00:26:13.565 --> 00:26:14.160
RON LIVINGSTONE:
Different body type.

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:14.515
CHARLIZE THERON: I--

00:26:14.515 --> 00:26:15.350
[LAUGHING]

00:26:15.350 --> 00:26:16.725
MACKENZIE DAVIS:
Different body--

00:26:16.725 --> 00:26:18.250
you don't know what it's like.

00:26:18.250 --> 00:26:19.750
CHARLIZE THERON:
Ron is, by the way,

00:26:19.750 --> 00:26:22.820
the nicest person you will ever
meet on the face of the earth,

00:26:22.820 --> 00:26:24.260
hands down.

00:26:24.260 --> 00:26:26.550
Way nicer than you.

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:30.302
So I'll just point
out you guys' best--

00:26:30.302 --> 00:26:31.385
MACKENZIE DAVIS: As foils.

00:26:31.385 --> 00:26:32.260
CHARLIZE THERON: Yes.

00:26:34.920 --> 00:26:36.420
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN:
Go ahead, Emma.

00:26:36.420 --> 00:26:38.086
AUDIENCE: Thank you
guys for being here.

00:26:38.086 --> 00:26:40.840
I'm just curious, was it
hard to get this movie made,

00:26:40.840 --> 00:26:43.300
given that it's a
movie about motherhood

00:26:43.300 --> 00:26:45.950
and being a new parent
and multiple kids?

00:26:45.950 --> 00:26:48.010
Was this a hard one to pitch?

00:26:48.010 --> 00:26:50.260
Or do you feel like there's
an appetite for that right

00:26:50.260 --> 00:26:53.750
now, how much we're
exploring motherhood,

00:26:53.750 --> 00:26:56.740
and you're seeing it
more in shows and films?

00:26:56.740 --> 00:26:59.272
JASON REITMAN: I don't think--

00:26:59.272 --> 00:27:01.230
they're traditionally
not easy to get financed,

00:27:01.230 --> 00:27:03.300
and I don't think they're--

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:06.060
I have not heard of any
studio out there saying,

00:27:06.060 --> 00:27:10.400
you know what, let's look
for more real human drama,

00:27:10.400 --> 00:27:12.360
particularly female human drama.

00:27:12.360 --> 00:27:13.880
That's-- although you're right.

00:27:13.880 --> 00:27:17.330
There's a lot more of that
happening in television now.

00:27:17.330 --> 00:27:20.660
I think-- frankly, a
company called BRON Studios

00:27:20.660 --> 00:27:23.750
up in Vancouver
financed this film.

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:27.020
And they came in early,
and they came in strong.

00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:28.910
They liked the script.

00:27:28.910 --> 00:27:33.020
They loved this cast, clearly,
and they backed the film.

00:27:33.020 --> 00:27:35.840
And they were amazing
start to finish.

00:27:35.840 --> 00:27:38.020
There was never any kind of--

00:27:38.020 --> 00:27:40.700
I never felt them trying to
bend it into something that it

00:27:40.700 --> 00:27:41.660
wasn't.

00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:44.084
The people that were
already big fans

00:27:44.084 --> 00:27:45.500
of "Juno" and
"Young Adult--" they

00:27:45.500 --> 00:27:48.990
got the tone of what we wanted
to do, and we got it made.

00:27:48.990 --> 00:27:50.990
But I feel lucky about that.

00:27:50.990 --> 00:27:52.490
I think we're very
fortunate that we

00:27:52.490 --> 00:27:53.760
got to get this film made.

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:54.740
There's a lot of
films like it that

00:27:54.740 --> 00:27:57.156
are trying to get made that
are not getting the financing.

00:27:57.156 --> 00:28:01.190
If only we were at a company
with a limitless amount

00:28:01.190 --> 00:28:07.010
of funds that could invest
into movies of tomorrow.

00:28:07.010 --> 00:28:11.040
I would think if they
really cared about women,

00:28:11.040 --> 00:28:14.960
they would start investing money
into female-driven independent

00:28:14.960 --> 00:28:16.740
film.

00:28:16.740 --> 00:28:17.240
Huh.

00:28:17.240 --> 00:28:18.448
CHARLIZE THERON: I like that.

00:28:21.650 --> 00:28:25.460
AUDIENCE: My question goes to
