00:28:37.526 --> 00:28:38.890
AUDIENCE: Yeah, pretty much.

00:28:38.890 --> 00:28:40.330
CHARLIZE THERON: It's
a Tolkien crossover.

00:28:40.330 --> 00:28:40.913
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:28:43.997 --> 00:28:46.580
I'm just really curious to know
what your directing process is

00:28:46.580 --> 00:28:51.710
like, from getting the script
in your hands to development,

00:28:51.710 --> 00:28:56.150
pre-production, post-production,
to distribution--

00:28:56.150 --> 00:28:57.560
how much was changed?

00:28:57.560 --> 00:29:00.050
What was left--
what was left in?

00:29:00.050 --> 00:29:01.700
What was left out?

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:06.470
And how-- and through
those changes, how

00:29:06.470 --> 00:29:12.798
did you define the characters
from point A to point B?

00:29:12.798 --> 00:29:17.120
And what was it like to
pick out the color palette

00:29:17.120 --> 00:29:20.810
for cinematography and
choosing the appropriate lenses

00:29:20.810 --> 00:29:21.950
to tell the story?

00:29:21.950 --> 00:29:22.450
I'm sorry.

00:29:22.450 --> 00:29:24.158
JASON REITMAN: These
are a lot of-- these

00:29:24.158 --> 00:29:25.530
are all great questions.

00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:28.640
It's a lot of them,
and I think if I

00:29:28.640 --> 00:29:31.742
were to answer all of that,
it would take a while.

00:29:31.742 --> 00:29:32.450
And I'm going to.

00:29:32.450 --> 00:29:34.760
So-- no.

00:29:34.760 --> 00:29:40.220
So I'll just say a
couple of brief things.

00:29:40.220 --> 00:29:48.240
One, what's unique about Diablo
is that she is a pure writer

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:52.800
and does not use index
cards or treatments.

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:54.240
She has an idea.

00:29:54.240 --> 00:29:56.236
She called me at
one point and said,

00:29:56.236 --> 00:29:58.110
I have this idea for a
movie, and she kind of

00:29:58.110 --> 00:29:59.940
told it to me in two sentences.

00:29:59.940 --> 00:30:03.360
And then six weeks later,
she had a screenplay,

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:07.920
and it was a first draft, but
it was also our shooting draft.

00:30:07.920 --> 00:30:09.300
And she just writes.

00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:11.820
She sits down and starts
at the first scene, then

00:30:11.820 --> 00:30:14.760
the second scene, and she
lets the movie tell her

00:30:14.760 --> 00:30:16.320
what its going to be.

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:18.890
And that's how she's
written all her films.

00:30:18.890 --> 00:30:22.557
And as another writer,
it's infuriating.

00:30:22.557 --> 00:30:24.890
I mean, it took me seven years
to write "Up in the Air."

00:30:24.890 --> 00:30:27.440
I don't know-- I don't
know how she does it.

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:30.070
But her screenplays are
very clear on the page,

00:30:30.070 --> 00:30:32.090
and it's not to say
that they are loaded

00:30:32.090 --> 00:30:34.294
with long paragraphs of detail.

00:30:34.294 --> 00:30:35.210
They're very succinct.

00:30:35.210 --> 00:30:36.290
They're very short--

00:30:36.290 --> 00:30:37.760
100-page scripts.

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:42.200
But you can't help but read
it and know what she's saying

00:30:42.200 --> 00:30:44.120
and what she's referring to.

00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:47.750
I feel like it's my job not to
tell the actors how to do it.

00:30:47.750 --> 00:30:49.310
It's to find people
who I think have

00:30:49.310 --> 00:30:51.590
connective tissue with the
characters on the page.

00:30:51.590 --> 00:30:53.240
Not that they're the
same human being,

00:30:53.240 --> 00:30:55.460
but there's something inside
them that connects them

00:30:55.460 --> 00:31:00.215
to this character that I know
is going to come to life.

00:31:00.215 --> 00:31:02.090
And then they bring it
to life, and I'm there

00:31:02.090 --> 00:31:09.410
to help shape and keep us
all within one tonal world.

00:31:09.410 --> 00:31:12.950
But it's up to them,
and we don't rehearse.

00:31:12.950 --> 00:31:15.350
We-- and it's funny
you brought that up.

00:31:15.350 --> 00:31:19.190
We had one lunch before
we went because I'm lucky.

00:31:19.190 --> 00:31:22.822
I get to work with brilliant
actors, and I know, on the day,

00:31:22.822 --> 00:31:23.780
we're going to find it.

00:31:23.780 --> 00:31:25.988
And we're going to find it
over a few takes, or maybe

00:31:25.988 --> 00:31:28.580
a few more takes, but it's not
going to be anything crazy.

00:31:28.580 --> 00:31:32.750
And when that magic
happens, when two actors--

00:31:32.750 --> 00:31:35.780
when two really talented actors
suddenly connect and have

00:31:35.780 --> 00:31:38.719
chemistry, and the
lines come to life,

00:31:38.719 --> 00:31:40.260
there's nothing like
it in the world.

00:31:40.260 --> 00:31:42.830
I mean, it's really an exciting
thing to watch happen live,

00:31:42.830 --> 00:31:44.871
and when it happens, I
want the cameras to be on.

00:31:44.871 --> 00:31:46.862
I don't want to be in
a rehearsal studio.

00:31:46.862 --> 00:31:49.070
So that's a little bit of
how the process was, and it

00:31:49.070 --> 00:31:51.524
certainly is how this
movie came together.

00:31:51.524 --> 00:31:53.815
JENNIFER VAN FOSSEN: I think
we have one more question,

00:31:53.815 --> 00:31:55.706
and then we'll wrap up.

00:31:55.706 --> 00:31:57.580
AUDIENCE: So Charlize
and Ron, I think of you

00:31:57.580 --> 00:32:00.992
both as really funny
people who play characters

00:32:00.992 --> 00:32:02.950
with a lot of pain, but
really funny characters

00:32:02.950 --> 00:32:05.550
with a lot of pain.

00:32:05.550 --> 00:32:08.540
But you also do some
wackier characters,

00:32:08.540 --> 00:32:12.520
and I'm sort of curious,
as artists and performers,

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:15.680
do you feel like that
balance is important?

00:32:15.680 --> 00:32:17.180
Or do you lean one
way or the other,

00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:18.596
that it's important
to you to play

00:32:18.596 --> 00:32:21.813
characters who have some sort
of non-comedic painful depth?

00:32:21.813 --> 00:32:24.609
RON LIVINGSTONE: Wow,
that's a great question.

00:32:24.609 --> 00:32:25.525
You want to take that?

00:32:25.525 --> 00:32:27.750
Or--

00:32:27.750 --> 00:32:29.500
CHARLIZE THERON: No,
I could go after you.

00:32:29.500 --> 00:32:30.502
RON LIVINGSTONE: All right.

00:32:30.502 --> 00:32:31.918
You know what, I'm
going to assume

00:32:31.918 --> 00:32:33.810
my male privilege to go first.

00:32:33.810 --> 00:32:34.784
[LAUGHING]

00:32:34.784 --> 00:32:36.450
CHARLIZE THERON: I'm
handling it to you.

00:32:40.110 --> 00:32:41.950
RON LIVINGSTONE: I-- it's like--

00:32:41.950 --> 00:32:44.410
I think the pain is--
everybody has pain.

00:32:44.410 --> 00:32:48.890
And so if it's useful to
bring it to the thing,

00:32:48.890 --> 00:32:50.710
then that's great.

00:32:50.710 --> 00:32:54.310
As far as the wacky, I just--

00:32:54.310 --> 00:32:57.010
I think I'm just kind of goofy.

00:32:57.010 --> 00:33:00.250
There's an element of
me that's kind of goofy.

00:33:00.250 --> 00:33:03.280
And there was a while-- there
was five years when I was

00:33:03.280 --> 00:33:06.910
trying to be a matinee idol
and wear the leather jacket--

00:33:06.910 --> 00:33:08.260
I mean, like I have on now.

00:33:08.260 --> 00:33:14.050
And it was just really hard not
to make a face because there's

00:33:14.050 --> 00:33:18.100
something about it that
strikes me as a little silly.

00:33:18.100 --> 00:33:22.780
And then that's the part that
I like about it, is OK, what's

00:33:22.780 --> 00:33:24.640
the silly part?

00:33:24.640 --> 00:33:26.615
But I think it's all the same.

00:33:26.615 --> 00:33:27.490
You know what I mean?

00:33:27.490 --> 00:33:34.000
It's like people who are only in
pain or only trying to be funny

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.120
tend to be really infuriating
people to hang out with,

00:33:37.120 --> 00:33:38.560
so you just throw
it all together

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:42.250
and see what comes out of it.

00:33:42.250 --> 00:33:45.240
CHARLIZE THERON: Yeah, I
mean, I agree with Ron.

00:33:45.240 --> 00:33:51.940
I don't believe that
people are only one thing.

00:33:51.940 --> 00:33:53.320
I think that--

00:33:53.320 --> 00:33:55.750
I think that's also what
makes this writing feel

00:33:55.750 --> 00:34:03.610
so great because it deals with
some very serious and hard

00:34:03.610 --> 00:34:07.340
subject matter, but
through real people.

00:34:07.340 --> 00:34:08.750
And I think real people--

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:10.330
I think we can all
relate to that.

00:34:10.330 --> 00:34:15.800
I've had shitloads of
tragedy, but nobody is just

00:34:15.800 --> 00:34:16.699
that one thing.

00:34:16.699 --> 00:34:19.270
And I think a lot of people
who have had a lot of tragedy

00:34:19.270 --> 00:34:23.380
in their life tend to veer
more towards the silly

00:34:23.380 --> 00:34:28.530
and the light-heartedness
of it in order to survive.

00:34:28.530 --> 00:34:32.190
I mean, this is why
I'm dead inside.

00:34:32.190 --> 00:34:33.550
Didn't work for me.

00:34:33.550 --> 00:34:38.760
But I think there's a
sense of humor about this

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:39.949
that feels very real.

00:34:39.949 --> 00:34:43.300
That's not just a joke for the
sake of a joke or to be funny.

00:34:43.300 --> 00:34:44.969
I think a lot of the
humor of this film

00:34:44.969 --> 00:34:48.060
comes from very
real places, and I

00:34:48.060 --> 00:34:50.210
know for myself,
raising my kids,

00:34:50.210 --> 00:34:55.530
it is a horror movie and
a comedy with Will Ferrell

00:34:55.530 --> 00:34:58.590
and "Star Wars."

00:34:58.590 --> 00:34:59.490
It's everything.

00:34:59.490 --> 00:35:01.600
It's literally
every day, I'm like,

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:03.360
I don't know what
movie we're in today,

00:35:03.360 --> 00:35:08.220
but can't wait to go on the
ride, see where it lands.

00:35:08.220 --> 00:35:08.950
I don't know.

00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:09.630
Does that-- is that--

00:35:09.630 --> 00:35:09.952
RON LIVINGSTONE: That was great.

00:35:09.952 --> 00:35:10.630
CHARLIZE THERON: That
was a bullshit answer.

00:35:10.630 --> 00:35:11.260
JASON REITMAN: I
thought it was good.

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:11.430
CHARLIZE THERON: I don't--

00:35:11.430 --> 00:35:12.750
RON LIVINGSTONE: Yeah.

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:13.020
JASON REITMAN: I'm satisfied.

00:35:13.020 --> 00:35:14.270
CHARLIZE THERON: I don't know.

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:14.942
I don't know.

